description:
It seems like when I use the cursor as a read stream and I use `map` on the cursor, the map function is applied twice.

Example:
{code}
client.collection('xxx')
  .find()
  .project({ _id: 1 })
  .map(doc => {}}
    return { doc: doc };
  })
  .on('data', x => console.log('data', x));
{code}

Output:
{code}
data { doc: { doc: { _id: '5bb55dd0d6eb334f45811b8e' } } }
data { doc: { doc: { _id: '5c54e86c7e37c22ce904cd71' } } }
data { doc: { doc: { _id: '5c5dcaec66b2983808d4b1bb' } } }
data { doc: { doc: { _id: '5c953939a1650802df5b28fa' } } }
data { doc: { doc: { _id: '5c968877c666b318f01a84c0' } } }
data { doc: { doc: { _id: '5c953300654c60739c20f783' } } }
{code}
 
Expected:
{code}
data { doc: { _id: '5bb55dd0d6eb334f45811b8e' } }
data { doc: { _id: '5c54e86c7e37c22ce904cd71' } }
data { doc: { _id: '5c5dcaec66b2983808d4b1bb' } }
data { doc: { _id: '5c953939a1650802df5b28fa' } }
data { doc: { _id: '5c968877c666b318f01a84c0' } }
data { doc: { _id: '5c953300654c60739c20f783' } }
{code}

At [https://mongodb.github.io/node-mongodb-native/3.4/api/Collection.html#aggregate], I see:
{noformat}
Specify collation (MongoDB 3.4 or higher) settings for update operation (see 3.4 documentation for available fields).{noformat}
Is the "update operation" bit a copy/paste error? Also, what exact documentation is the last parenthesis referring to?

From user [~peter.broadhurst@kaleido.io]:

We've had to pin our version to 3.5.3 as this code change changed behaviour.

Simple sample recreate of the change in behavior:
{code}
async function run() {
  const MongoClient = require('mongodb').MongoClient;
  const client =  await MongoClient.connect(process.env.MONGODB_URL);
  const db = client.db('354regr');
  const collection = db.collection('numbers');
 
  try {
    await collection.deleteMany({});
    for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) await collection.insertOne({i});
    let cursor = await collection.find({});
    cursor.limit(5);
    while (await cursor.hasNext()) {
      const doc = await cursor.next();
      console.log(`Doc: ${JSON.stringify(doc)}`);
    }
  }
  catch(err) {
    console.error(err.stack);
  }
 
  client.close();
}
run()
{code}

Output with mongodb@3.5.3 (or mongodb@3.5.2 and previous) - see the limit of 5 records returned as expected:
{code}
Doc: {"_id":"5e6012c0bab232836f58f35b","i":0}
Doc: {"_id":"5e6012c0bab232836f58f35c","i":1}
Doc: {"_id":"5e6012c0bab232836f58f35d","i":2}
Doc: {"_id":"5e6012c0bab232836f58f35e","i":3}
Doc: {"_id":"5e6012c0bab232836f58f35f","i":4}
{code}

Output with mongodb@3.5.4:
{code}
Doc: {"_id":"5e601344f32806839a905a99","i":0}
Doc: {"_id":"5e601344f32806839a905a9a","i":1}
Doc: null
MongoError: Cursor is closed
    at Function.create (/private/tmp/node_modules/mongodb/lib/core/error.js:43:12)
    at Cursor.hasNext (/private/tmp/node_modules/mongodb/lib/cursor.js:197:24)
    at run (/private/tmp/t/index.js:12:25)
    at process._tickCallback (internal/process/next_tick.js:68:7)
{code}
See that each time hasNext is called, it seems to be consuming one of the limit entries, resulting in a null doc being returned on the third call to next() and the cursor being closed.

Originally reported [here|https://github.com/Automattic/mongoose/issues/8637]

If a lambda passed to {{withTransaction}} results in a rejected promise with no reason, the driver assumes a valid value and tries to check for an [error code|https://github.com/mongodb/node-mongodb-native/blob/b1187c3d17df045b302737ade88517f9f26b653e/lib/core/sessions.js#L377-L385].

For example, this will fail: 
{code}
const session = await client.startSession()
await session.withTransaction(s => Promise.reject());
{code}

[https://github.com/mongodb/js-bson/issues/384] 

As described in the issue, the inner logic for determining whether to serialize as Long/Double is never reached because of the outer condition for:
{quote}{{value >= constants.JS_INT_MIN &&}}
 {{value <= constants.JS_INT_MAX}}
{quote}
However, simply removing the outer condition causes [these tests to fail|https://github.com/mongodb/js-bson/blob/master/test/node/bson_test.js#L1168-L1172].

It's not immediately clear how we should deserialize Longs which are larger than {{Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER}}.

